Preamble

The European Union, hereinafter referred to as "the Licensor", represented by the
European Commission (the "Commission") as the operator of the Joinup collaboration
platform, has developed the European Union Public Licence (EUPL) as an open source
licence.

The EUPL is a licence under European law to be used by natural or legal persons
(hereinafter: the "Licensee" or "Licensees") copying, distributing, communicating and/or
modifying a work (hereinafter: the "Work") or works.


Article 1
Definitions

1.1. 'Work'
    means any work or software, as well as any material protected by copyright law in
the literary, artistic or scientific domain.

1.2. 'Derivative Work'
    means any work or software directly derived from the Work or from another
derivative work of the Work.

1.3. 'Source Code'
    means the preferred form in which a computer program is made available to the
public, including the underlying code and the accompanying material such as
comments and documentation.

1.4. 'Object Code'
    means any form resulting from mechanical transformation or translation of a
Source Code or parts thereof, which can be executed by a computer.

1.5. 'Licence'
    means this document.

1.6. 'Contributor'
    means any natural or legal person that creates or contributes to the creation of
modifications to the Work within a Project.

1.7. 'Project'
    means a set of files, including an executable file, and its Source Code, where the
work on the computer program has been organised. Every version of the set or any of
its components can be a Work to which this Licence is applied.

1.8. 'Compatibility Matrix'
    means the table located at the following URL
    https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/eupl/external-licence-compatibility-eupl
    which is part of the Licence and which may be updated from time to time to reflect
the evolution of the Licence and the compatibility with other licences. If a Work
is integrated in a larger work, the conditions of the Licence are applicable to that
part which is subject to the EUPL. Any use of a Work that is not covered by this
Licence is outside the scope of this Licence and remains subject to the licence
terms covering that use.

1.9. 'Notice'
    means the copyright notice, the patent notice, the disclaimer of warranty and the
    limitation of liability provided in Article 5 of the Licence.


Article 2
Scope of the Licence

2.1. The Work is provided under the terms of this Licence, to the maximum extent
possible, to any person obtaining a copy of the Work from the Licensor or from a
Licensee.

2.2. This Licence applies to any work or software, and to any other copyrightable
material in the literary, artistic or scientific domain that is distributed, or
communicated with the Work or part of it, or attached to it.


Article 3
Acceptance

3.1. The Licensee shall accept all the terms of this Licence by performing any act
that would, in the absence of this Licence, be restricted by copyright on the Work,
including but not limited to use, copy, modify, merge, publish, distribute, communicate,
reproduce, and create Derivative Works.

3.2. The Licensee may explicitly express its acceptance of the Licence by affixing a
copy of the Licence to the Work.


Article 4
Licensees' rights

4.1. The Licensee is granted a worldwide, royalty-free, non-exclusive, sublicensable
licence to do the following, for the duration of copyright on the Work:

a) use the Work in any circumstances and for all use, commercial or non-commercial;

b) reproduce the Work;

c) modify the Work and make Derivative Works based upon the Work;

d) communicate to the public, distribute or publish the Work or any Derivative Work;

e) lend and rent the Work or any Derivative Work;

f) sublicense rights in the Work or any Derivative Work under any licence of the
Licensee's choice.

4.2. The rights mentioned in Article 4.1 may be exercised on all media and by all
means, with or without modifications, for any purpose, namely commercial or
non-commercial.

4.3. The Licensee may grant commercial licences on the Work or Derivative Works under
different terms and conditions, provided that these licence agreements respect the
terms and conditions of this Licence or are compatible with them.

4.4. The Licensee may use a copy of the Work as a starting point for a new software
product, then develop and modify it to create a Modified Work different from the
original Work, and license, or otherwise provide, the Modified Work to others
under different licence terms, including a proprietary licence, provided that such
licence terms do not attempt to limit the Licensee's rights under this Licence.


Article 5
Obligations of the Licensee

5.1. The Licensee shall maintain the copyright notices on all copies of the Work
released. The Licensee shall ensure that all parts of the Source Code of the Work that
are to be published are given a copyright notice.

5.2. The Licensee shall ensure that all the copies of the Work, which the Licensee
communicates, publishes or distributes, are marked with the Notice (as defined in
Article 1.9) in a conspicuous place. If the Work is in Source Code form, the Notice
shall be included in each file of the Source Code of the Work that includes a
copyright notice. In the case of a Derivative Work, the Notice shall be included in
each file that includes a copyright notice.

5.3. The Licensee shall include a copy of the Licence with every copy of the Work
or Derivative Work that the Licensee communicates, publishes or distributes. Such copy
may be in any form (including electronic, paper or written media).


Article 6
Patent rights

6.1. The Licensee is granted a worldwide, royalty-free, non-exclusive licence to use
any patent claims held by the Licensor to the extent necessary to make, use, sell,
offer for sale, import or otherwise transfer the Work, where such licence applies
only to those patent claims licensable by the Licensor that are necessarily
infringed by the Work as provided by the Licensor under this Licence, when making,
using, selling, offering for sale, importing or otherwise transferring the Work
